\tThe Confederate diplomats have been engaged in discussions with the Europeans for a long time now, in their attempt to get recognized as an independent sovereign nation. Whilst their reception in Europe was warm, the British and the French were unwilling to take sides in the American Civil War. With the recent Confederate victories, the tone has completely changed.\n\tWith the Confederate armies showing the world that they can challenge and defeat the Union military, foreign intervention becomes increasingly likely. The British are preparing an expeditionary force and the French in Mexico are willing to open up a new trade route to Texas, and even to send military forces over the Rio Grande, if the Confederacy would offer open support for the Mexican intervention.
