538
The Western part breaks away from the State of Virginia.
\tThe recent campaigns in Western Virginia and the Kanawha Valley have been a great success for the Confederate armies, they now control this mountain region bordered by the Ohio River in the West. With the Union forces removed from the area the local Unionist citizens, who voted against secession in early 1861, fleeing the area, consolidating Confederate support. Any plans of breaking away from Virginia are thwarted.\n\tGeographically this is a stinging blow to the Union. Whilst mountainous and a difficult terrain to support armies in, Western part of Virginia offered them a route to undertake operations to threaten the upper Shenandoah Valley. Controlling the area, Confederate troops have effectively cut the Baltimore & Ohio Railroad, the main life-line connecting Washington and the Western states.
