Saltville Captured by Union!
Confederate Salt Production Weakened!
Further Raids in Florida and Louisiana!


537
Saltville, Virginia, has been Captured by Union forces.
\tSalt is important during times of war, as it is used to preserve food and curing leather. "Salt is eminently contraband," as one Union general put it. Recent Union operations have captured Saltville, Virginia, severely hampering Confederate salt production.\n\tConfederate salt comes mainly from salt plants in Florida coast, rock salt deposits in Avery Island, Louisiana, and from Saltville salt works in Virginia. Realizing the criticality of this commodity, Union has conducted coordinated raids to these locations. As a result, salt prices are rapidly increasing and distribution of salt is regulated. For example in Georgia, a half-bushel of salt costs 2,50 dollars. For a widow who has a son in the Confederate army, the price is one dollar.
